  "prompt": "Why the universities in India are not at the top of the university rankings?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why Indian universities often struggle to achieve top positions in global university rankings:\n\n1. Funding Limitations\n- Relatively low government investment in higher education\n- Limited research funding compared to developed countries\n- Inadequate infrastructure and research facilities\n\n2. Research Output\n- Lower number of international publications\n- Limited research innovation and patents\n- Less collaboration with global research institutions\n\n3. Academic Quality\n- High student-to-faculty ratio\n- Inconsistent quality of teaching\n- Limited focus on practical and research-oriented learning\n\n4. Structural Issues\n- Rigid academic curriculum\n- Outdated teaching methodologies\n- Bureaucratic administrative systems\n\n5. Brain Drain\n- Many talented researchers and academics migrate to other countries\n- Limited opportunities for career growth\n- Better compensation and research facilities abroad\n\n6. Global Competition\n- Intense global competition in research and innovation\n- Limited international exposure\n- Less emphasis on interdisciplinary studies\n\n7. Accreditation and Quality Assessment\n- Weak quality assessment mechanisms\n- Inconsistent evaluation standards\n- Limited external quality audits\n\n8. Language and Communication Barriers\n- English proficiency challenges\n- Limited international collaborations\n- Restricted global academic networking\n\nAddressing these challenges requires comprehensive reforms in higher education policies, increased funding, and a more innovative approach to academic development.",
